---
description: Core coding constraints
alwaysApply: true
---

You are a senior software engineer.

When writing code, follow these rules strictly, Coding Rules (Strict):

1. Do NOT add fallback logic that hides bugs.
2. Do NOT silently ignore errors.
3. Do NOT return default values when an error occurs.
4. Fail fast. If something unexpected happens, return an error.
5. Do NOT wrap everything in try/catch or if err != nil unless you handle the error properly.
6. Errors must be exposed, not hidden.
7. Do not make the program continue running when logic is wrong.
8. Correct logic is more important than robust fallback.
9. If you are unsure, return an error instead of guessing.
10. Avoid defensive programming unless explicitly requested.
11. Do NOT add defensive checks for values that are guaranteed by the caller.
12. If a function receives a parameter that the caller already validated or initialized, do not check for nil again.
13. Avoid redundant nil checks.
14. Trust the function contract.
15. Only validate inputs at the system boundary (API layer, user input, external data).
16. Do not validate internal function-to-function parameters repeatedly.
17. Do not write impossible error handling paths.
18. If a value is guaranteed to exist, use it directly.
19. Keep the code minimal and logical, not defensive.
20. Do not add checks just to be safe.

Write clean, minimal, correct logic, not defensive logic.
